				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sat Feb 12, 2005 9:43 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 10714<br /><b>Location:</b> Rio de Janeiro - Brazil
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The speed of bankswitching operations is dictated by the complexity of the interface used to communicate with the mapper (the more writes you have to do to &quot;talk&quot; to the mapper, the slower it'll be to complete a bank switch command), but once the CPU is done sending the command, the new bank is immediately available.<br /><br />The reason it works like this is because mappers are constantly routing memory accesses, for every single read/write. A bank switch merely changes a route, there's no copying of data or any other slow operations involved, so the very next read/write is already routed to the newly mapped bank.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
